Hey hey hey everyone… just wanted to share this super easy beginner friendly way to do stitch braids… I tried to slow down the pre part method as slow as I could to give you guys an understanding… no it doesn’t take long to pre part but it definitely helps to get clean, crisp and precise lines when stitching… of course there are several different ways to do stitch braids… but I taught myself this way when I first started doing them and it helped soooo much… 
.
.
When you section your hair… put whatever product you use on both sides and down the middle… comb and smooth both sides to the middle and then start pre parting… you want to make make sure that each section is smooth and flat before you twist it to the middle… you repeat the process until the entire section is complete… you can then either do the stitch feed in braid or you can go ahead and pre part a few more sections… 
.
.
Again… this is not the only way to do this style but just one of the ways that I teach how to do stitch braids in my online classes… not only do I show this way… but I show how to part as you go with your index fingers, with your pinky fingers, how to part the first row… part the section down the middle and stitch side to side and d how to do the rubber band method… so yep there are several different ways I show you but this by far has been the easiest for me and my students!!! 
.
.
Let me know in the comments how you’re feeling about this method!!! 
.
.

Hey hey hey Good Morning Beautiful People!! I hope that y’all are doing Fantabulously Well on this Beautiful day!!! Just wanted to hop on this morning and show y’all this very easy beginner friendly Bantu knots tutorial… Now before anyone goes in… I know Bantu Knots are not for everyone… I know these Bantu knots are on the chunky side… but my client requested them to be this size!  Again… it’s not for everyone but I have had people ask how to do them… soooooo here goes…
.
.
Sorry no voice over this time 😂😱😂
But first… you part your section and smooth it down with the product that you’re using ( I’m using my edge control… Royal edges) 
- once you have your section smoothed, part it across into 2 sections
- place the weave in the center of the part
- take the two sections of the clients hair and place it into a ponytail over the weave
- detangle and smooth clients real hair and weave, start twisting all the hair clockwise
- once you start twisting all the hair clockwise, twist down in a spiral pattern
- once you get to the bottom, tuck the hair or place a rubber band around the knot
.
.
For natural hair twist outs… skip the weave and ponytail steps
- smooth section of hair to the middle and twist clockwise and down in a spiral pattern
.
.
Or you can smooth the section of hair
- do a two strand twist
- once the twist is complete… twist the two strand twist clockwise and then down in a spiral pattern.
- when you get to the bottom, you can either tuck it or secure with a rubber band
.
.
I hope this tutorial helps some… again I know this style isn’t for everyone but for the ones who would like to know here you go lol… 
.
.
This is just a snippet of how I teach it in my classes… not only do I show you how but how to style them… make sure to follow me and turn on notifications to be the first to know when the classes drop!!! 
.

Can I share something with my Braiders/ Stylists/ Nail Techs/ Barbers/ Entrepreneurs and Small business owners… Just something to think about… I seen a post about pricing and I was like she is spot on but can we take it a step beyond that… 

I know in the beauty industry (especially) and just being a business owner in general… we get the “oh that’s too much” “that’s not worth it” “I can find it somewhere else cheaper” “blah blah blah” when it comes to pricing but my question is… can you keep your business up and running with a persons negative opinions about your prices?? 

No? I didn’t think so… 

Just some food for thought.. Did you know that making 6 figures is very attainable? How you say? Let me give a tidbit… 

$100,000 minimum for one year salary 

Say you unrealistically work 365 days per year. No days off… if you do and you make a minimum of $275 per day (working 7 days per week)… you will reach your goal in one year.

Ok… now realistically speaking… say you take off 8 days per month… every weekend… that means you would only be working 269 days per year… if you do and you make a minimum of $375 per day (5 day work week)… you will reach your goal in one year… 

5 days a week.. that’s still too much work? Trust me.. I get it… let’s say you work 4 days per week… that means you’re only working 221 days per year… if you make $455 per day (4 day work week)… you will reach your goal in one year! 

Basically what I’m saying is … make sure that whatever income goal you set for YOUR business is strictly that and not based on how people feel about your pricing.. you can’t take an opinion to the bank, cash it and pay bills can you? 

Just think about it… and once you hit that first 6 figures… 10X it and keep on going!!!

Hey hey hey Happy Monday everyone!!! I hope that you all are having a MARVELOUS MONDAY so far… just wanted to hop on for a sec and show the process of how I do my braided ponytails… it doesn’t matter if you’re doing small, medium or large size braids for the ponytail… you can still use this method…  remember the ultimate goal is to have the least amount of tension possible…
.
.
Whether you’re doing a high or low ponytail… start off by parting across from ear to ear.. You will have a front section and a back section.. 
.
.
Mid way through your part, part a u shape on the both and same thing for the top section… once you have finished parting, it should look like a circle…
.
.
Part each half in half again giving you four sections in your circle… 
.
.
I prefer to do Knotless in the middle for less tension but you can do Knotless or Box braids in the middle… 
.
.
 Once you have your middle for braids… Make a part straight down the middle (giving you 4 sections to work with)
.
.
Then start your feed in or stitch braids until the ponytail is complete… 
.
.
That’s it… that’s the process… let me know if this was helpful by dropping a 👍🏽 or a 👎🏽 in the comments… also… if you have any questions about how to do a braid or particular style… drop that in the comments as well so that I can make a video showing how to do it…

Hey hey hey everyone!!! I have had a few ppl ask about stitch braids… how to do them and a few other questions… so here’s a tutorial on the basics of stitch braids…
.
.
Depending on the size of the stitch braid… 
- use product on both sides and down the middle… 
- smooth(mold) hair to where the braid will be placed… 
- (whenever possible) start out braiding your clients real hair…
-  keep uniform stitches by holding your clients hair and the added hair securely as you are braiding..
.
.
The purpose of this video is to show that there is not just one way to do a stitch braid… there are multiple ways… whether you prepare, part as you go with your index finger, pinky finger, ring finger, use a comb or a comb and finger method… they all will produce the same look…

I always get the question, how do I become faster with braiding? Here are the 3 tips that I always share and I will share a few more as well and also a HUGE NO NO!!! 
.
.
1. PRACTICE, PRACTICE, PRACTICE and then PRACTICE some more! Practice DOES NOT make you PERFECT but it WILL help you become GREATER in your skill, technique and craft. Even if you don’t have any clients, get a mannequin head and go to work! 

2. TIME YOURSELF!!! This is going to be key! If you don’t know where you’re at or where you’re starting from… then how will you know what you need to improve? Say you start out doing box braids at 6.5 hours but you want to get down to 4.5 hours… time yourself on the following… How long does it take you to part one braid? How long does it take you to braid one braid? How long does it take you to part an entire row? Etc

3. When doing Box braids, arch parts tend to work great. They can be easily parted with one swoop/stroke of the comb. The look is more natural and the braids lay flat in between each other. If arch parts aren’t your jam.. no biggie.. try other parting methods including pre parting. 

4. Make sure your braiding hair is out of the pack and separated. If you know what size braids you are doing, you can have the hair already separated per braid so that you can just grab and go.

5. Use product while braiding. I normally use Loc N for parting and shine n jam w/honey for braiding. Find the product that works best for you!
.

We will never forget it. But I was 13 maybe 14 back in the 1900s. Back when the braided bobs were in style. Mind you, I was only about a year or 2 into braiding. We were sitting on our front porch and I was doing a braided Bob on her. And of course you know back then, the ends were burnt. Well some way, some how… when I went to burn the end of one of the braids her hair (that I thought was in a ponytail) caught on fire just like at the beginning of this video and babyyyyyyyy you should have seen me patting her head trying to get them flames out… I almost knocked her out I was patting so hard… smh Mercyyyyy! It was truly an accident but HunnI our mama didn’t see it that way bc she beat the brakes off of me 😂 but whewwwww but lawd am I glad and I’m sooooo thankful for my sister bc she didn’t hold it against me and I still braid her hair till this day!

Hey hey hey Happy Monday everyone!!! I hope that you all are having a MARVELOUS MONDAY so far… just wanted to hop on for a sec and show the process of how I do my braided ponytails… it doesn’t matter if you’re doing small, medium or large size braids for the ponytail… you can still use this method…  remember the ultimate goal is to have the least amount of tension possible…
.
.
Whether you’re doing a high or low ponytail… start off by parting across from ear to ear.. You will have a front section and a back section.. 
.
.
Mid way through your part, part a u shape on the both and same thing for the top section… once you have finished parting, it should look like a circle…
.
.
Part each half in half again giving you four sections in your circle… 
.
.
I prefer to do Knotless in the middle for less tension but you can do Knotless or Box braids in the middle… 
.
.
 Once you have your middle for braids… Make a part straight down the middle (giving you 4 sections to work with)
.
.
Then start your feed in or stitch braids until the ponytail is complete… 
.
.
That’s it… that’s the process… let me know if this was helpful by dropping a 👍🏽 or a 👎🏽 in the comments… also… if you have any questions about how to do a braid or particular style… drop that in the comments as well so that I can make a video showing how to do it…
